04920nam a22006975i 9781501722394DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20181997nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017223947 a10.7591/97815017223942doi  a(DE-B1597)514811  a(OCoLC)1083589371  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aPOL0130002bisacsh04a610.69522211 aBudrys, Grace, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aWhen Doctors Join Unions /cGrace Budrys. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2018] 4c©1997  a1 online resource (192 p.) :b1 table  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- t1. Introduction -- t2. The Eruption of the Physicians’ Union Movement -- t3. Physicians’ Strikes tn the United States and Elsewhere -- t4. Professionalism: Construction of the Concept -- t5. The End of the Golden Age -- t6. The Union’s Formative Years -- t7. The Changing Environment in the 1980s -- t8. The Deprofessionalization of Medicine? -- t9. The Mature Organization -- t10. Why a Union and Not a Professional Association? -- t11. From Cottage Industry to the Modern Era: The Industrialization Model -- t12. Postindustrial Work: A New Class of Workers -- t13. Is It Legal for Doctors to Form Unions? -- t14. What Does the UAPD Do for Its Members? -- t15. A Physicians’ Union-Harbinger or Anomaly? -- t16. Other Unions and Their Future -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCurrent and anticipated changes in this country's health care system are likely to add momentum to the physicians' union movement, according to Grace Budrys. She documents the emergence and development of the Union of American Physicians and Dentists (UAPD), founded in the San Francisco Bay area in 1972, and suggests it may be a harbinger of renewed organizing efforts throughout the country.Representing both salaried and private practice doctors, the UAPD gained strength in the early 1980s during the crisis in malpractice suits, and surged again in recent years in response to steadily increasing medical corporatization. Budrys argues that the approach to modernization now favored across the country resembles that of the industrialization era. As health organizations become larger, more centralized, and more hierarchical, decisions are made further from the work site and some traditional responsibilities are delegated to lower-paid, less-trained workers.Nevertheless, the image of blue-collar industrial workers organizing into unions is not easily reconciled with our society's image of physicians as highly trained and highly skilled members of a profession long considered the bastion of individualists. Budrys suggests that doctors' unions in general and the UAPD in particular may provide a model for other nontraditional groups and occupations seeking solutions to contemporary problems in the workplace. After discussing the laws governing workers' organizing rights and their interpretation by the courts, she concludes with commentary on the organizing activity taking place among highly paid and highly educated workers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aCollective bargainingxPhysicianszUnited States. 0aPhysiciansxLabor unionszUnited States. 4aConsumer Health & Fitness. 4aLabor History. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Labor & Industrial Relations.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Archive Pre-2000z978311053617140uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150172239440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501722394423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501722394/original  a978-3-11-053617-1  Cornell University Press Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_BACK